metadata.name: Monsoon #38
metadata.description:
Optimization. It's something that haunts all programmers. Including me. But no longer! Monsoon is a study into the optimization of particle systems for the web. Looking especially deep into dynamic grids and dynamic frame rates.

As for the piece itself, it's a reference to how busy this modern world is. How we're all constantly on the go, whether that is physically, or mentally. Almost feeling like a monsoon. A storm of information. A storm of life. A storm of work. A storm of thoughts. A storm of emotions. A storm of everything. And it's all so fast.

As are the particles. They're all moving around these cyclones of information. Glowing up like neon signs in a busy city. Moving so fast it's almost a blur. Forming into something greater than the sum of its parts.

metadata.name: I like its informality #69
metadata.description:
“You can’t depend on your eyes when your imagination is out of focus.” — Mark Twain

The subtle animation captures the essence of focus and movement. The sharp angles of the triangles draw the viewer's gaze towards the center of the piece, where the lines converge and intersect. This central point of focus is further emphasized by the sweeping curves and dynamic shapes that flow outwards from it, creating a sense of motion and energy.

Overall, the combination of triangles, focus, and movement creates a sense of tension and drama, inviting the viewer to explore the piece and discover its hidden depths. Whether viewed up close or from a distance, this artwork is sure to captivate and engage the viewer with its dynamic interplay of form and movement.

Press *Space bar* to stop and restart the animation.
Press *e* to epxort the image as PNG in 4000x4000px.

Use the URL parameters *animated=false/true* to start with or without animation.

Stefan Schwaha, @sektionschef, https://digitalitility.com/

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #122
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png

metadata.name: Textura #67
metadata.description:
"Textura"

My initial goal was to create artwork that could trigger raw, visceral emotions and feelings. A polar opposite to the polite, clinical precision of some other collections, I wanted to embrace the grittier side of abstract art. 

This turned out to be a rather difficult project for me. It was a departure from my usual figurative / ink line style, where most of the time I find it straightforward to tell a "good" output from a "bad" one. Here, out of my comfort zone, I couldn't tell. I liked some outputs, I hated some. The ones I hated, usually would be someone else's favorites. Abstract art is hard !

After a while, some patterns started to emerge. The overall feedback was that, generally:
- blue outputs were peaceful
- orange ones were intense and aggressive
- black and white ones were oppressive and sometimes disturbing

If you can associate an emotion to any given output, I feel like I will have achieved my goal. Thank you to everyone who provided feedback !

 
Technically, this project also posed a number of challenges:
- how to blend a large number of procedural textures in a smooth, yet natural way
- how to make sure the final piece has some kind of depth, visible beyond the intricate layering
- how to optimize contrast and get vibrant results

This was mostly achieved by spending a lot of time designing and fine-tuning color schemes - enhanced versions of color palettes, that also contain pre and post-processing settings.

The collection features a total of 31 color schemes. 

Key commands:
'1', '2', '4': increase resolution
's': save png
'n': toggle background noise
'c': toggle background canvas texture

On mobile devices, the rendering resolution is reduced to deal with memory limitations.

metadata.name: Unit of me #93
metadata.description:
Just like a river, which is always flowing and changing, we are never the same from one moment to the next. Our individuality is composed of countless fragments, each with its unique size and color, that come together to form who we are at any given moment. These fragments constantly shift, some become more prominent and vibrant, while others fade into the background. We are constantly being molded and shaped by the passage of time, so that who we are today is not who we were yesterday, and will not be who we are tomorrow

13 color palettes
3 canvas proportion ratio
and more 3 different traits

Press S to save a .png

Created by Zamboni
Dec. 2022

metadata.name: Rill #70
metadata.description:
There is beauty in simplicity.
Creating a sense of calm, having proportion and symmetry in the form, Empty spaces are calculated, avoiding chaos and disorder, directing the viewer's gaze.
Despite its simple appearance, this interpretation of art is a complete work that contains many words.
Made by p5.js
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: 365 DivideRect #3
metadata.description: 365 DivideRect is a stunning piece of generative art that uses the divideRect() function to create a complex and intricate pattern. With each iteration, the function divides a rectangle into two new triangles, resulting in a self-similar and recursive structure. The piece is rendered using a vibrant and varied color palette, adding an additional layer of visual interest and complexity to the pattern. :)

metadata.name: Rug of imagination #58
metadata.description:
I recently faced covid, I can say it was one of the worst moments of my life, I questioned my sanity and if I would stay alive. What comforted me was to remember my childhood, my past, and I remembered the rugs I used to sit on to play or listen to stories, it is amazing how in the day to day we forget the little things in life that make us happy, sometimes we stop living to just survive.

Artwork made with p5.js and p5.scribbles

metadata.name: EDDY #235
metadata.description:
An eddy is a circular movement of water counter to a main current. It reminds me of innovations in art, like a small countercurrent to the mainstream, surfacing new techniques and aesthetics. 

I hope that EDDY will brighten your days with its playful swirl of colors, inspired by the sea, the sky, the birds, and post-impressionist paintings.

Keyboard Controls:
[F] Fill the window.
[S] Save the current view in live mode as an image (default 1125x1500px).
[1] [2] [4] [6] Change resolution, 1.5K to 9K.
[R] Reverse course.

Made with p5js and shaders.

Created by elsif, 2022.12.
